
[1]inveteracy

   INVET'ERACY, n. [L. inveteratio. See Inveterate.]

   Long continuance, or the firmness or deep rooted obstinacy of any
   quality or state acquired by time; as the inveteracy of custom and
   habit; usually or always applied in a bad sense; as the inveteracy of
   prejudice, of error, or of any evil habit.
